The '''Western Cape Department of Health''' is a [[government department|department]] of the [[Government of the Western Cape]], responsible for providing [[public healthcare]] to the population of the [[Western Cape]] province of [[South Africa]].

The political head of the department is the [[Minister of Health (Western Cape)|Provincial Minister of Health]]; {{asof|2010|lc=on}} this is [[Theuns Botha]] of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westerncape.gov.za/eng/gov_employees/180709 |title=Mr Theuns Botha |publisher=Western Cape Government |accessdate=29 August 2010}}</ref> The administrative head is the Superintendent-General of Health; {{asof|2010|lc=on}} this is Professor Craig Househam.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westerncape.gov.za/eng/gov_employees/52796 |title=Prof. Keith Craig Househam |publisher=Western Cape Government |accessdate=29 August 2010}}</ref>

In the 2010/11 financial year, the department had 27,993 employees and a budget of [[South African rand|R]]11,962,863,000.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.westerncape.gov.za/other/2010/3/vote_06a.pdf |chapter=Vote 6: Department of Health |title=Budget 2010: Estimates of Provincial Expenditure |isbn=978-0-621-39119-0 |publisher=Western Cape Provincial Treasury |location=Cape Town |date=2 March 2010 |accessdate=29 August 2010}}</ref>

==Hospitals==
In the Western Cape there are 428 public [[primary care]] facilities ([[clinic]]s and community health centres), some operated by the Department of Health, while others are operated by the [[City of Cape Town]] and funded by transfer payments from the department.<ref name="rep-serv">{{Cite book |title=Annual Report 2008/9 |url=http://www.westerncape.gov.za/Text/2009/11/annual_report_2008-09_health.pdf |page=14 |year=2009 |publisher=Western Cape Department of Health |location=Cape Town |date=28 August 2009 |accessdate=29 August 2010}}</ref>

Public [[secondary care]] services are provided by 32 district hospitals, six regional hospitals, and three central hospitals (which also provide tertiary care; see below).<ref name="rep-serv" />

Three central hospitals in [[Cape Town]] provide [[tertiary care]]; these are [[Groote Schuur Hospital]], [[Tygerberg Hospital]], and [[Red Cross War Memorial Children's Hospital]]. They take specialist [[Referral (medicine)|referrals]] from other hospitals across the province, and in many cases from other provinces or even other African countries.

The department also runs various specialised facilities, including six [[tuberculosis]] hospitals, four [[psychiatric hospital]]s, and a [[Physical medicine and rehabilitation|rehabilitation]] centre.

